ຢູ່​ໃນ​ເບື້ອງ​ຫລັງຂອງ​ເທັກ​ໂນ​ໂລ​ຈີ ການ​ຕິດຕາມ​ອຸນຫະພູມ ​ໃນ​ເຮືອນ​ຊານ​ຂອງ​ພວກ​ເຮົາ ​
ແລະ ສະພາບ​ດິນ​ຟ້າອາກາດ ​ໃນ​ເຮືອນແກ້ວ​ຂອງ​ກະ​ເສດ​ຕະກອນ.
ທ່ານນາງ Genevieve Bell ຈາກ​ບໍລິສັດ INTEL ​ເວົ້າວ່າ “​ໃນ​ອະນາຄົດ ບໍ່​ແມ່ນ​ດຽວ​
ນີ້ ​ແຕ່​ໃນ​ອະນາຄົດ ພວກ​ເຮົາ​ຈະ​ມີຫຼາຍສິ່ງ ຫຼາຍຢ່າງ ຢູ່​ໂລກ​ຂອງ​ພວກ​ເຮົາ ຢູ່​ໃນ​
ເຮືອນ​ຊານ​ຂອງ​ພວກ​ເຮົາ ຢູ່​ໃນ​ທຸລະ​ກິດ​ຂອງ​ພວກ​ເຮົາ ຢູ່​ໃນ​ລົດ​ຂອງ​ພວກ​ເຮົາ ​
ແມ່ນ​ວ່າ ຈະ​ເຊື່ອມ​ຕໍ່​ເຂົ້າກັນ.”
ທ່ານ​ນາງ Bell ກ່າວ​ອີກ​ວ່າ ມັນ​ກຳລັງເລີ້ມ​ເກີດ​ຂຶ້ນ​ແລ້ວ ​ແລະ ວ່າ​ນັບແຕ່ການ​ເດີນທາງ ​
ຕະຫລອດທັງ ການ​ຂົນ​ສົ່ງ ແລະ​ການ​ຜະລິດ​ພະລັງງານ ​ເທັກ​ໂນ​ໂລ​ຈີ​ທີ່​ໄດ້​ຖືກ​ຕິດຕັ້ງ
ຢູ່ພາຍ​ໃນ ​ແມ່ນ​ກຳລັງ​ເຮັດ​ໃຫ້​ລະບົບ​ຕ່າງໆ​ ຂອງ​ພວກ​ເຮົາ​ນັ້ນ ມີ​ປະສິດທິພາບຫຼາຍຂຶ້ນ.
New computer applications are changing the ways we live and work, from travel to manufacturing.Mike O'Sullivan spoke with developers at a recent forum in San Francisco about trends in technology that is embedded and connected.
A virtual reality viewer works with a smart phone and another is embedded in eyewear.They're the devices that make news.
(DOUG DAVIS, INTEL)
"Those are the ones that as consumers we see, and those are kind of exciting.But we're starting to see a big impact in areas like industrial or manufacturing.You're now connecting machines in factories and analyzing data in ways you never were able to before."
The German company ProGlove is integrating scanning and motion tracking functions into gloves for factory workers, to keep track of inventory.
(SEBASTIAN PETRUCH, PROGLOVE)
"We mainly focus on automotive manufacturing and logistics, and, in these industries, you have a very high efficiency pressure."
The transformation is far-reaching.The Ebola crisis led to a portable system to store and retrieve patient records at isolated clinics in Africa.
(KEN KRIEGER, HARDWARE ENGINEER)
"Something that can be sterilized, dunked in chlorine to kill the Ebola, and would support being used in very rugged, really hostile environments for technology."
Behind-the-scenes technology keeps track of temperatures in our homes and climate conditions in a farmer's greenhouse.
(GENEVIEVE BELL, INTEL)
"In the future, not right now but in the future, we will have a whole lot of things in our world, in our homes, in our businesses, in our cars that are connected."
She says it is starting to happen, and that from commuting andshipping to energy production, embedded technology is making our systems more efficient.
